ce:section.ce:para:
In the first phase of synthesis, the graphite oxide (GO) is obtained from graphite powder using Hummer s method [27]. The GO is then characterized by using field emission scanning electron microscope (FESEM). The FESEM showed the agglomerated form of GO (Fig. 1
                     ) with 60.3 % of carbon, 33.7 % of oxygen and very small percentage of hydrogen (Fig. 2
                     ). The GQD is then synthesized with nitric acid method mentioned in [28,38] with some weight percentage modification. Initially, 2.5 g of GO is oxidized using concentrated HNO3 and H2SO4 using low frequency ultrasonication for 50 Hrs. The synthesized solution is then cooled down to room temperature and further diluted by using 1300 ml of DI water. The dilute solution is then centrifuged at 4500 rpm to isolate from the un-exfoliate material and which is further diluted using DI water. This colloidal solution is then dialyzed by using the dialysis bag for 6 hrs. After this process, the acidic group is removed by mixing this colloidal solution with DI water (90 ml) and ammonia solution (125 ml). This suspension is then sonicated using probe type sonicator and further stirred for 3 hrs at 100 °C. After cooling down this suspension at room temperature, it is centrifuged at 20000 rpm. The transformation of GQD to AGQD is identified by using high resolution transmission electron microscope (HRTEM) imaging (Fig. 3
                     ). The formed suspension is then concentrated using rotary type evaporator at 60 °C. After this, suspension is dried off in a vacuum oven to obtain powdered form of AGQD. This powdered form of AGQD is utilized as nanomaterial to form PAG-AGQD based nanosuspension.

In the second phase, the obtained AGQD is dispersed in PAG oil using probe type ultrasonicator. Three concentrations of 100 ppm, 200 ppm and 500 ppm for PAG-AGQD nanosuspension are synthesized. The synthesized nanosuspension is kept still for 48 hrs (Fig. 4
                     ). This time period is required to observe the sedimentation that occur due to gravity effect. As sedimentation was not visible, after 48 hrs the UV spectra analysis was performed to evaluate the colloidal stability of synthesized dispersions. For 100 ppm, 200 ppm and 500 ppm AGQD-PAG approximate absorbance is found to be 2.9, 2.4 and 1.45 at wavelength of 270 nm, 275 nm and 310 nm respectively. Further, the synthesized nanosuspension was kept still for two months and then again UV spectra analysis was performed for all the nanosuspensions. After two months, all the synthesized nanosuspension have shown better results. From UV spectra analysis it is found that the absorbance of all the concentrations are decreased. However, the absorbance value is maintained nearly at over 75 % for all the three concentrations even after two months (Fig. 5
                     ). The Table 1
                      and Table 2
                      show the details of used chemicals and instruments to synthesize and inspect the nanosuspension. The Table 3
                      shows the thermophysical properties of pure PAG oil used as base fluid for PAG-AGQD nanosuspension.

The thermal conductivity of synthesized AGQD – PAG based nanosuspension has shown better enhancement as compared to the conventional PAG lubrication oil. The pattern of gain in thermal conductivity is obtained by the Hamilton model as well as with physical experimentation. The results from the Hamilton model and experimentation show the impact of quantum dots concentration on thermal conductivity. As the quantum dots concentration in the nanofluid (AGQD – PAG based nanosuspension) increases, the thermal conductivity of the PAG enhances. The gain of thermal conductivity is accounted to the availability of more surface area in the lubrication oil. The colloidal form of AGQD nanoparticle in the PAG oil provides extra room for the transfer of heat, which as a result improves the thermal conductivity of the lubrication oil [26,38,48]. Along with it, as the nanoparticle concentration of quantum dots increases the specific heat of nanosuspension is found to decrease. The similar behavior is observed while evaluating the specific heat experimentally. On an average, theoretical and experimental results show that by using AGQD-PAG based nanosuspension of 100 ppm, 200 ppm, and 500 ppm concentration, thermal conductivity enhances by 29.5 %, 40 %, and 92.2 % respectively (Fig. 8
                        ) and specific heat reduces by 2.26 %, 3.7 % and 5.86 % respectively (Fig. 8). Similar types of trends using different nanomaterial have been reported by the researchers[78–81]. The small deviation in the thermal conductivity as well as in specific heat is observed between the theoretical model and experimentation, but the predicted trend by theoretical model of both observed parameters have shown a similar pattern of incremental thermal conductivity (Fig. 8) and decremental specific heat (Fig. 9
                        ).

Due to the addition of quantum dots in the nanosuspension, the density of the nanosuspension slightly increases. [82]. The density of the nanosuspension is evaluated theoretically and experimentally, and in either of the two cases the density is found to be increase [83–85]. As the density of the nanosuspension increases the viscosity of nanosuspension is also found to be increase. The viscosity of the AGQD – PAG-based nanosuspension is evaluated by using the Brinkman model (Fig. 10
                        ) and rotational viscometer (Fig. 11
                        ) at different temperature ranges. The experimental results, as well as that of Brinkman model, show the gain in viscosity with an increase in the concentration of the quantum dots. The Brinkman model value is observed to be quite higher as compared to the viscometer value. It is caused as the Brinkman model does not account for the heat losses while in experimentation those losses affect the value of the viscosity. On an average, theoretical and experimental result shows that gain in viscosity (at 45 °C) and density using 100 ppm, 200 ppm, and 500 ppm is around 9.6 %, 28.5 %, 55.8 % and in density is around 3.43 %, 8.65 %, 11.8 % respectively (Fig. 10, Fig. 11 and Fig. 12
                        ). Beyond 500 ppm, viscosity increases at a high rate, and the quantum dots get agglomerated. Hence the experimentation is restricted to 500 ppm only. The higher viscosity (that achieved beyond 500 ppm of nanosuspension concentration) makes nanosuspension unstable [86], hence the lower concentrations of quantum dots are being used during the experimentation. Similar trends of viscosity and density have been observed using nanoparticle in other lubrication oil and with other 2D material.

To make sure that compressor should not surpass its higher- or low-pressure limit, the compressor discharge pressure is observed while using incremental mass of R134a refrigerant with different concentrations of AGQD-PAG based nanosuspension. With the increase in AGQD-PAG based nanosuspension concentration, the compressor discharge pressure is found to decrease (Fig. 15
                        ). The presence of AGQD-PAG based nanosuspension enhances the thermal conductivity of the conventional PAG oil, which in turn improve the thermal conductivity of refrigeration oil mixture [93]. This phenomenon enhances the vapor quality (Eq. (17)) at the suction side i.e. at evaporator exit, correspondingly higher refrigerating effect is observed resulting in improvement in COP [65–68]. The gain in vapor quality using varying concentration of AGQD-PAG based nanosuspension is illustrated in Fig. 16
                        .

The use of AGQD-PAG based nanosuspension is observed to impact the pressure drop. The pressure drop in the system occurs due to the friction between the refrigerant and tube wall. As the nanomaterial are anti wear and anti-frictional in nature [96,97], the utilization of it with refrigerant oil mixture reduces the friction between the wall tube and refrigerant [60,73,75,77]. In the current research work, the pressure drop for AGQD-PAG based nanosuspension refrigerant mixture is evaluated theoretically (Eq. (33)) and experimentally. The experimental results show that the pressure drop in the evaporator section is increased in less amount with increasing AGQD concentration (Fig. 18
                        ). Similar trend is observed in result as predicted by mathematical model. However, the pressure drops in the mathematical model is comparatively lesser due the non-consideration of gravity and momentum of refrigerant oil mixture in the mathematical model. Also, the mass flow rate shows slightly increasing trend with nanoparticle concentration. As the refrigerant mass is increased slightly in current experiments, it does not reflect any major variation in mass flow rate (Fig. 19
                        ). However, if the compressor speed in rpm increases, the trend of decrease in mass flow rate has been observed using oxide-based nanomaterials [72].
